’ extensive experience. It includes new species and genera; addresses changing nomenclature; and provides details about polypores’ biology, morphology, composition, role as parasites, interactions with various arthropods, and purported medicinal applications. The book also highlights how changes in geology, soil structure, and plant species due to factors such as continental drift and climate change have affected the evolution of polypores. Featuring more than 240 species of polypores, extensive and easy-to-use dichotomous keys, and more than 300 color illustrations and multiple maps and line drawings, it is a must-have for amateur and professional mycologists, forest service personnel, mycophagists, and anyone interested in learning more about this remarkable group of fungi.‹/p›  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aPolyporaceaezNorth AmericavIdentification. 0aPolyporaceaezNorth AmericavPictorial works. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh  apolypores, fungi, field guide, fungi identification, biology, morphology, mycophagists, mycology, mushrooms.1 aBessette, Arleen R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSmith, Dianna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074527640uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32272740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477322734423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477322734/original  a978-3-11-074527-6  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK